# Testing Principles

Adapted from Kent C. Dodds' testing principles:
<https://github.com/kentcdodds/kentcdodds.com/blob/main/docs/agents/testing-principles.md>

- Prefer small, readable tests with explicit setup and minimal magic.
- Prefer flat test files with top-level tests; avoid deep `describe` nesting.
- Avoid shared setup (`beforeEach`/`afterEach`) unless it clearly improves readability.
- Do not test behaviour already guaranteed by the type system.
- Build helpers that return ready-to-run objects; avoid global mutable fixtures.
- Make test names describe user-visible or service-visible behaviour.
- Prefer behaviour assertions over implementation details. Avoid pinning CSS classes, incidental markup, or exact headers unless they are the contract.
- Keep tests offline-friendly: use local fixtures/fakes instead of public internet or third-party services.
- Prefer fast unit tests for server logic; reserve browser/e2e tests for important user journeys.
- Keep test-only setup in test harnesses/helpers, not production env branches or query parameters.
- Use disposable resources only when there is real cleanup to perform.
- When adding e2e coverage, default to happy-path journeys; only keep edge-case e2e tests when lower-level tests cannot credibly cover the behaviour.
